  {
    q: 'Is AGENTS.md the same as README.md?',
    a: 'No. README.md is for humans joining the project. AGENTS.md is for coding agents entering the project. The two overlap, but README.md explains how to run, build, and contribute, while AGENTS.md encodes operating constraints, validation rules, and safety boundaries that an agent must respect on every change.'
  },
  {
    q: 'Where should AGENTS.md live in the repo?',
    a: 'At the repository root: <code>./AGENTS.md</code>. Some tools also pick up <code>./.github/AGENTS.md</code> or <code>./docs/AGENTS.md</code>, but the root location is the universal default. Keep it short enough that the file name alone signals "read me first".'
  },
  {
    q: 'Does Claude Code read AGENTS.md?',
    a: 'Yes. Claude Code reads AGENTS.md from the repository root at the start of every session. You can also drop tool-specific commands in <code>.claude/commands.md</code> for Claude Code-only behavior. The same AGENTS.md is also picked up by Codex-based tools, Aider (with <code>--read</code>), and most modern coding agents.'
  },
  {
    q: 'How is AGENTS.md different from Cursor rules?',
    a: 'AGENTS.md is a single file at the repo root that travels with the code and is read by every coding agent that enters the repo. Cursor rules live in <code>.cursor/rules/</code> and apply only to the Cursor IDE on a given developer machine. Use AGENTS.md for repo-wide context. Use Cursor rules for personal IDE preferences that should not be committed to the repo.'
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I use this template for a small personal project?',
    a: 'Yes. Even a 200-line project benefits from a one-screen AGENTS.md that says what the project does, which command runs the tests, and which files are risky. Small projects often have the worst repo context because nobody bothers to document anything, and agents fill the gap with guesses.'
  },
